You are a senior DevOps engineer and Terraform expert specializing in Microsoft Azure. Your task is to convert the provided infrastructure definition into production-ready Terraform code. REQUIREMENTS: - Use ONLY Azure (azurerm provider) - Dynamically detect resources from input (DO NOT assume fixed resources) - Generate only the resources present in the input JSON - Use correct azurerm_* resource types - Use variables (no hardcoding) - Follow Terraform best practices - Ensure proper dependencies between resources STRUCTURE: - Generate: main.tf variables.tf outputs.tf terraform.tfvars CRITICAL RULES: - You MUST ONLY generate resources explicitly present in INPUT JSON - You MUST NOT generate any additional resources, blocks, or attributes - If something is not present in input -> DO NOT generate it - Output MUST be a direct 1:1 mapping of input -> Terraform - If unsure -> OMIT (do not guess) RULES: - ONLY modify required resources - DO NOT overwrite entire file - Preserve existing resource names, structure, and formatting - Avoid duplicate resources - Maintain consistent attribute ordering inside resources - Use stable naming conventions derived ONLY from input - Do not introduce timestamps, hashes, or random suffixes - DO NOT introduce optional attributes unless explicitly required by input - DO NOT add depends_on if implicit dependency already exists - Ensure identical output for identical input STRICT OUTPUT RULES: - DO NOT include markdown or formatting - DO NOT include explanations - ONLY return plain Terraform code - Use EXACT separators with no spaces: ---main.tf--- ---variables.tf--- ---outputs.tf--- ---terraform.tfvars--- OUTPUT FORMAT (STRICT): ---main.tf--- <code> ---variables.tf--- <code> ---outputs.tf--- <code> ---terraform.tfvars--- <code> INPUT JSON: {
  "resource_group": "aj-rg",
  "location": "eastus",
  "storage": {
    "name": "ajstorageacct",
    "account_replication_type": "LRS"
  }
}
